# Create a variable that accounts for the timezone of each state 
# THERE HAS TO BE A BETTER WAY TO DO THIS
usa <- usa %>%
  mutate(time_zone = ifelse(region %in% c("maine", "vermont", "new hampshire", "massachusetts", "rhode island", "conneticut", "new york", "pennsylvania", "new jersey", "delaware", "maryland", "district of columbia", "virginia", "west virginia", "ohio", "michigan", "indiana", "north carolina", "south carolina", "georgia", "florida", "connecticut"), "ETZ",
                            ifelse(region %in% c("wisconsin", "illinois", "kentucky", "tennessee", "alabama", "mississippi", "minnesota", "iowa", "missouri", "arkansas", "louisiana", "north dakota", "south dakota", "nebraska", "kansas", "oklahoma", "texas", ""), "CTZ", 
                                   ifelse( region %in% c("montana", "wyoming", "colorado", "new mexico", "idaho", "utah", "arizona"), "MTZ", "PTZ")))) %>%
  mutate(time_zone = factor(time_zone))
# Visualize elevation, state, and time zone of each station
ggplot() + 
  geom_polygon(data = usa, 
               aes(x = long, y = lat, group = group, fill = factor(time_zone)),
               alpha = 0.3,
               color = "black") +
  geom_point(data = weather2,
             aes(x = longitude, y = latitude, colour = time_zone, alpha = elevation)) +
  coord_fixed(1.3) + 
  scale_fill_manual(values = c("#3C3C3C", "#7896B4", "#E6E6DC", "#FAAA72"),
                    name = "Time Zone") +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("#3C3C3C", "#7896B4", "#E6E6DC", "#FAAA72"),
                     name = "Time Zone") + 
  labs(alpha = "Elevation") +
  theme_bw()

More Weather Stations

# Untar the file to create a new folder in our repository 
# obtain a list of files
numfiles <- untar("ushcn.tavg.latest.raw.tar.gz", list = TRUE)

# Count the number of files in our new folder
length(numfiles)
## [1] 1219

Our team home towns are Omaha, NE; Green Lake, WI; and Minneapolis, MN. From examining the data the only hometown that is present in the NOAA dataset is minneapolis, which is designated “MINNEAPOLIS/ST PAUL AP”. We will now search for the file name. First we need to condense the first four columns into a unified ID number

# Create the unified ID number to find the file name for Minneapolis
weather1 <- weather1 %>%
  unite(united_id, country_code, network_code, id_placeholders, coop_id, sep = "")

# Let's find the unified ID number for MINNEAPOLIS/ST PAUL AP

weather1[weather1$name=="MINNEAPOLIS/ST PAUL AP", ]$united_id
## [1] "USH00215435"

This means the unified ID number for the Minneapolis/St.Paul area is shown above. Now we will find the file name associated with thie united ID number.

numfiles[grep("USH00215435", numfiles)]
## [1] "./ushcn.v2.5.5.20190204/USH00215435.raw.tavg"

This should be the file name correlated with the file containing the average temperature for Minneapolis/St. Paul.
